         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W. ¶ March 26/65 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ I write a few lines to acknowledge the receipt of yours of the 9th Jany which came to hand yesterday — with some notes on Cucurbitaceae etc. Dr ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">65.03.26</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times, Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">March 26/65</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I write a few lines to acknowledge the receipt of yours of the 9th Jany which came to hand yesterday — with some notes on <name key="Cucurbitaceae">Cucurbitaceae</name> etc. Dr Hooker has worked up <name key="Cucurbitaceae">Cucurbitaceae</name> &amp; <name key="Passifloreae">Passifloreae</name> for the Genera Plantarum<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83), vol. 1, part 3 (published in 1867).</p>
               </note> and has been in correspondence on the subject with Naudin Dr Hooker has investigated them with great care from dried specimen and Naudin has taken as much pains with those especially which he has been enable<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">enabled?</p>
               </note> to cultivate at Paris during several years he has devoted to them — so that I hope that altogether I shall have less difficulty with the genera than I had anticipated With regard to the <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> I get on but slowly on account of the tedious labor of examining such vast numbers of an order comparatively new to me — at least the capsular ones — for I had previously examined a large number of tropical baccate <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> — Your <name key="Chamaelaucieae">Chamaelaucieae</name> (all but one parcel) were sent off in a box made up for you at Kew as I mentioned in my last <name key="Baeckea">Baeckea</name> Leptospermum and their allies are also ready but I do not send them just yet as I have still some old synonyms — as well as a few of Schauers &amp; Turczaninow's to verify — Indeed among the <name key="Chamaelaucieae">Chamaelaucieae</name> it is possible that there may still be a name or two to alter</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I quite agree with you as to the great multiplication of species of Leptospermum<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to G. Bentham, 12 December 1863, and B64.02.01, pp. 60–2. </p>
               </note> but I am much at a loss where to stop with the uniting them for the whole of the genus seems to me to show a gradual passage from the one to the other — and yet I feel it will never do to unite all into one species — I shall give such characters as I can. You will probably consider the forms I admit as species to be mere varieties and other botanists whose views I feel also bound to respect will consider even my varieties as distinct species. I quite agree with you in uniting Fabricia with Leptospermum — I doubt much whether F. myrtifolia Gaertn has winged seeds It is a plant of which I find no specimens from any where but Endeavour Bay Banks and Solander's specimens with flowers and open capsules do not appear to have good seeds and Cunningham's are in the same state. What Gaertner figures as the seed appears to me to be the placenta with the whole mass of seeds perfect and sterile but none of them ripe which in that state are readily detached in one mass shaped exactly as Gaertner represents<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Gaertner (1787-91), vol. 1, p. 174; tab. 35, fig 4.</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Homalospermum">Homalospermum</name> again must come in as a species allied to F. laevigata — the perfect seeds are usually if not always winged as in that species. I think <name key="Pericalymma">Pericalymma</name> must also come in to Leptospermum, it is certainly very near L. erubescens in habit &amp; the ovules are the same only fewer in number — <name key="Agonis">Agonis</name> appears to me a good genus both in habit and its erect ovules. <name key="Kunzea">Kunzea</name> as you say has the ovules of Leptospermum but has exerted stamens.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In Metrosideros I am surprised that Australia has no representative of the typical Pacific Island &amp; N. Zealand form of the genus Your M. eucalyptoides belongs to the section of M. vera which forms Miquel's genus <name key="Nania">Nania</name> but which I think must be kept as a section of Metrosideros M. chrysantha and M. paradoxa on the other hand belong to Brongniart &amp; de Gris's New Caledonian genus <name key="Fremya">Fremya</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Brongniart &amp; Gris (1863), p. 372.</p>
               </note> over which your name <name key="Xanthostemon">Xanthostemon</name> has the rights of priority and which I think the alternate leaves and very different placentation will justify us in retaining as a genus.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have also done <name key="Kunzea">Kunzea</name>
               <name key="Eremaea">Eremaea</name> &amp;c and must now attack <name key="Callistemon">Callistemon</name> &amp; <name key="Melaleuca">Melaleuca</name> which appear to me to be a formidable task.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Profr Oliver has been working up <name key="Loranthaceae">Loranthaceae</name> with great care<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Oliver (1864).</p>
               </note> — but I think they will have to be transferred to the vicinity of <name key="Proteaceae">Proteaceae</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am glad to see that you have sent off Umbelliferae etc. — I still think <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name> must come into my 3d vol but there is plenty of time yet for I not see my way quite clearly through <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> yet — I not see however how they can exceed 600.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours very sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dr F. Mueller</p>
